name: Cnabetius

attributes.attribute: inscriptions found in Celtic regions of Germany and Austria
linked by scholars with such wounded kingly figures as the Irish Nuada
connected with Cnabetius by the Romans

sources: Monaghan, Patricia. The Encyclopedia of Celtic Mythology and Folklore. Checkmark Books, 2008.
text: Cnabetius is a Continental Celtic deity who is referred to as “the crippled one.” Though not much is known about this god, inscriptions have been discovered in Celtic areas of Austria and Germany. Scholars have associated him with injured royalty like the Irish Nuada, while the Romans drew comparisons between Cnabetius and their protective war god, Mars.
